<p>It bears repeating &#8211; all new nuclear weapon states have followed &#8216;traditional&#8217; (if you will) routes to acquire weapons. This is because it is the simplest, cheapest, and most reliable path.  Also, posturing to the contrary aside, the international non-proliferation apparatus/bureaucracy, really cannot stop any nation from doing what it pleases inside its own borders. Consequently there is no good reason to follow some untried idea, should some country come to the desision to mount a nuclear weapons program.</p>
<p>Furthermore, at best these alternate designs are harder than the standard ones, so they are no risk from non-state actors, who would already have an insurmountable task, building a simpler HEU based device.</p>
<p>As for other technology coming to fore, it is hubris of the worst kind to believe this can be stopped or controlled. History is at the very least, is clear on that.</p>
