<p>Well to a certain extent they HAVE bought the leadership of most major parties. However despite the fact that the lower echelon elected members (what we call back-benchers in the Commonwealth system) normally have little influence, they still need to be elected, and have in the past forced change because of public opinion. The fact is no amount of lobbying or slush funding is going to outweigh the threat of a significant number of them losing their seats.</p>
<p>Look at the history of most hot-button issues, and you will see politicians voting to save their asses, regardless of party position.</p>
